    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>Φίλων Α<unclear>υ</unclear>νακου
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
               <listApp>
                   <app><note>text based upon photographs</note></app>
                   <app loc="line 1"><note>Sofia 2018: Φιλ<unclear>ο</unclear>ν<unclear>α</unclear>[.]<unclear>ιακου</unclear></note></app>
               </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Philon son of Aunakos</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The name Φίλων is extremely common; Αυνακος on the other hand is only attested on the other plinth of this tomb, <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic004415">ISic004415</ref>. This plinth is one of a pair on a single base - a type attested several times in this necropolis - and the second plinth (<ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic004415">ISic004415</ref>) is also inscribed and the presence of the name Αυνακος in the genitive as its second element there suggests that the tomb is a double one for siblings.  The same situation seems to be attested in the case of <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic004417">ISic004417</ref> / <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic004418">ISic004418</ref>. The first name here appears to be in the nominative (which has a parallel in <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001208">ISic001208</ref>), rather than the more commonly found genitive in this necropolis. The lettering of this text is both larger and cruder than on the companion text, and less carefully set out, suggesting a different hand.</p>
            </div>
